 <!-- What does LP9 mean -->
 <section style="padding:3rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-card-bg);">

 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 What does life path number 9 mean?
 </h2>
 <div class="space-y-4 text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 <p>
 Life path 9 is the Humanitarian. The number of completion, wisdom, universal care. As the last of the single digits, 9 carries resonance with the entire cycle: something of 1's leadership, 2's sensitivity, 3's expression, 4's discipline, 5's adaptability, 6's love, 7's depth, 8's power. Distilled into a broader, more universal orientation toward the world.
 </p>
 <p>
 LP9 is here to serve something larger than themselves. Not aspiration, but pull. The 9 who tries to build a purely personal life, disconnected from contribution or larger purpose, feels something fundamental missing. Meaning comes through the larger work: the cause, community, creative vision, people who need what they can offer.
 </p>
 <p>
 The core challenge: including themselves in the care they extend to the world. LP9 gives to strangers, causes, people they barely know. Meanwhile neglecting their own needs, relationships, inner life. The 9 who balances universal care with personal presence becomes one of the most fully realized people in any room.
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Traits image + intro -->
 <section class="py-16 px-4">
 <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-10 items-center">
 <div>
 <div class="mb-8 rounded-lg overflow-hidden border border-border/60 shadow-lg">
 <img
 src="/images/learn/Life Path Number 9 - Traits.webp"
 alt="Life Path 9 - The Humanitarian personality traits"
 class="w-full h-64 object-cover"
 />
 </div>
 </div>
 <div>
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 Personality traits of life path 9s
 </h2>
 <p class="text-muted-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
 There's a quality to LP9 that people describe as old. Not old-fashioned, but old in the sense of having seen things. Talking with LP9 produces the feeling they've already been where you're going. That knowing, hard to explain, immediately recognizable, is LP9's most defining characteristic.
 </p>
 <p class="text-muted-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
 LP9 is magnetic. Broad perspective and lack of agenda make people feel safe to talk, share, open up. LP9 listens without needing anything from the conversation. Rarer than it sounds. Deeply attractive to anyone who's been around strategic listeners.
 </p>
 <p class="text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 Underneath the wisdom and care is complexity LP9 doesn't always show. Their own struggles, unfulfilled desires, grief. Often more than they let on because they're so accustomed to being the one others turn to that they don't know where to put what they're carrying.
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Strengths and challenges -->
 <section style="padding:3rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-card-bg);">
 <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2" style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
 Strengths &amp; Challenges
 </h2>
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
 <div>
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold font-[family-name:var(--font-family-heading)] text-body-text mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
 <span class="text-rpg-green text-xl">✦</span> Core Strengths
 </h3>
 <div class="space-y-4">
 {strengths.map(s => (
 <div class="card-light p-5">
 <div class="font-semibold text-body-text mb-1">{s.title}</div>
 <p class="text-sm text-muted-text leading-relaxed">{s.desc}</p>
 </div>
 ))}
 </div>
 </div>
 <div>
 <h3 class="text-lg font-bold font-[family-name:var(--font-family-heading)] text-body-text mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
 <span class="text-rpg-red text-xl">✦</span> Key Challenges
 </h3>
 <div class="space-y-4">
 {challenges.map(c => (
 <div class="card-light p-5">
 <div class="font-semibold text-body-text mb-1">{c.title}</div>
 <p class="text-sm text-muted-text leading-relaxed">{c.desc}</p>
 </div>
 ))}
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Love and relationships -->
 <section class="py-16 px-4">
 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 Life path 9 in love &amp; relationships
 </h2>
 <div class="space-y-4 text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 <p>
 LP9 in love is generous, understanding, and capable of a remarkable amount of patience. Being loved by a 9 often means feeling more seen and accepted than you've felt anywhere else. They don't love conditionally. The warmth is real and it goes deep.
 </p>
 <p>
 The complexity in LP9 relationships comes from the size of their orientation. The 9 who is called to serve humanity, or a cause, or a community, is going to bring a lot of that energy outward. For a partner who needs to feel like the center of LP9's world, this can be hard. LP9 isn't withholding love; they're distributing it broadly, which is a different problem but a real one.
 </p>
 <p>
 LP9 also carries an idealistic streak in relationships. They're looking for someone who shares their values, who cares about the world, who is working on themselves. When a real person doesn't quite measure up to this internal model, and real people rarely do, fully, LP9 can struggle between acceptance and disappointment.
 </p>
 <p>
 The strongest pairings for LP9 are LP7 (shared depth, philosophical resonance, comfortable with complexity), LP6 (mutual care, shared orientation toward something larger), and LP5 (LP9's wisdom gives LP5 direction; LP5's energy keeps LP9 present). The more challenging combinations are LP1 (LP1's self-orientation can feel small to LP9) and LP4 (LP4's pragmatism and LP9's idealism can create persistent friction).
 </p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Compatibility table -->
 <section id="compatibility" style="padding:3rem 1.5rem;background:var(--color-card-bg);">
 <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2" style="text-align:center;">
 Life path 9 compatibility
 </h2>
 <p class="text-center text-muted-text mb-10 max-w-xl mx-auto">
 How life path 9 pairs with each of the other life path numbers - based on shared values, complementary energy, and where things tend to become complicated.
 </p>
 <div class="overflow-x-auto">
 <table style="width:100%;font-size:0.875rem;border-collapse:collapse;border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:8px;overflow:hidden;box-shadow:0 2px 12px rgba(26,21,40,0.07);">
 <thead>
 <tr>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Life Path</th>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Archetype</th>
 <th class="text-center px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider">Match</th>
 <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider hidden md:table-cell">Notes</th>
 </tr>
 </thead>
 <tbody>
 {compatibility.map(row => (
 <tr>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-violet text-base">{row.lp}</td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-body-text font-medium whitespace-nowrap">{row.label}</td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-center whitespace-nowrap">
 {Array.from({length: 5}).map((_, i) => (
 <span class={i < row.score ? "text-gold" : "text-border/40"}>★</span>
 ))}
 </td>
 <td class="px-4 py-3 text-muted-text hidden md:table-cell">{row.verdict}</td>
 </tr>
 ))}
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>
 <p class="text-xs text-muted-text mt-4 text-center">
 Compatibility ratings reflect general patterns across life path numbers. Individual charts always add nuance.
 </p>
 </div>
 </section>

 <!-- Career -->
 <section class="py-16 px-4">
 <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
 <h2 class="section-h2">
 Career paths for life path 9
 </h2>
 <div class="space-y-4 text-muted-text leading-relaxed">
 <p>
 LP9 thrives when their work connects to something meaningful - not just a paycheck, but a genuine contribution to people or to the world. Humanitarian work, activism, nonprofit leadership, counseling, teaching, medicine, and public service all align naturally with LP9's deep need to be of use. So does any creative work oriented around human experience: writing, filmmaking, music, theater.
 </p>
 <p>
 LP9 brings a remarkable quality of understanding to any role that requires working with people through difficult situations. Grief counselors, social workers, doctors, lawyers serving vulnerable populations - LP9 has both the emotional capacity and the perspective that makes these roles sustainable in a way they aren't for everyone.
 </p>
 <p>
 The career risk for LP9 is overgiving in the professional sphere, which mirrors the risk in personal life. Taking on too much, absorbing too much of other people's pain without processing their own, working in environments that extract without replenishing - LP9 is vulnerable to burnout in ways that creep up rather than arrive suddenly.
 </p>
 <p>
 What LP9 needs from a career: the sense that what they do matters to someone. A role they can believe in. Colleagues and an organization whose values align with their own. The purely transactional career, good pay, no meaning, costs LP9 more than they often want to acknowledge.
 </p>
